<p>
Matthew Adams Dolan

Photo: Ben Morris

<p>“I have always been intrigued by the evolution of American style, which is so firmly rooted in ideas of tradition, legacy, and familiarity. In a way, I guess it is the opposite of originality. However, on the other hand, it really radicalized and reshaped how people, not only in America but the rest of the world, dressed. For instance, the idea of democratizing clothing that could be worn by men or women, and selling a lifestyle or an attitude which was so different from how people dressed before. Designers are always looking at the past, what has already been done, and how it relates to the current social climate. Now, more than ever, we are bombarded by imagery and references, so knowing and respecting that history is important; this idea of originality comes from reimagining that past from a different and personal perspective. I believe it is really important to be aware of how people wear clothes. At the end of the day, it’s not so much about changing the world or reinventing the wheel—it's about creating your own version of it.” —Matthew Adams Dolan </p>


